The MISRA for-loop rule applies to each for statement present in the function text after preprocessing and also requires considering the behaviour of functions called within a for statement; therefore the following are necessary to determine whether any for loops exist in or are injected into this function and whether they are well‑formed:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro): This macro is invoked directly at the top of the function and may expand into inline code (checks, returns, assertions). If it expands to any for loops (or modifies variables used in loops), those loops must be checked.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro): Used to obtain record/timebase pointers. This macro often expands into indexing or helper calls (and possibly inline code). Its expansion must be inspected for any for statements or expressions that could violate the rule.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken (function/macro): Frequently used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET to compute an index from the token; if implemented as a macro or inline helper it may contain for loops that become part of the function after preprocessing.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById (function): Called directly to obtain the token. If this is implemented as an inline function or macro in the same translation unit, its body (including any for loops) must be examined.

- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel (functions): These are helpers invoked by OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the static call graph). If any of these are inlined or macros they could introduce for loops or side effects relevant to loop-analysis and must be checked.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease (function): Called to release the token; if implemented as inline/macro it could contain for loops or modify objects used by loops in this function.

- OS_global_timebase_table, OS_timebase_table (objects/macros): Their definitions (e.g., as arrays, accessor macros) may be referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; if accessors expand to loops they must be inspected.

- memset, strncpy (library functions/macros): These are called in this function. While typically provided by the C library, if they are implemented as macros or inlined in this build they could contain for loops; include them to be thorough.

- OS_TimeBaseGetInfo_Impl (function): Called with &token; if implemented inline/macro it might contain for loops that affect compliance.

- OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl and OS_TaskGetId_Impl (functions): Although these are simple calls used to check context, if implemented as macros/inline functions they might introduce for loops or modify objects used in loops; include them to ensure no for loops are injected into the function body via expansion.

In short: inspect all macros used in the function (OS_CHECK_POINTER, OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET) plus any helper functions that those macros rely on (OS_ObjectIndexFromToken) and any callee implementations that might be inlined or macroized (ObjectId* helpers, OS_ObjectIdGetById, OS_ObjectIdRelease, OS_TimeBaseGetInfo_Impl, memset/strncpy). Only by examining these definitions/expansions can you be certain there are no for statements introduced into this function text or that any for statements present are well‑formed per the MISRA rule.
